{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8075b7db-b096-400a-b7b1-8785ac202ca5","content":"**Use `dotnet workload update`.**\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After a SDK update, this is what brings your MAUI workload back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the *same* versions already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a new SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** Your workloads are *outdated*, not *corrupted*, so:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after that, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm `maui` (or `maui-android`, `maui-ios`, etc.) appears, and reinstall any missing ones with `dotnet workload install maui`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b1f61d7d-82a8-4002-9246-d7f13b48db93","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task.","outputTokens":266,"requestId":"7FC8:229004:61D7058:6A9B1FE:69F155ED"},"id":"75ab583c-0ecb-40f5-9572-ab16c2bd1efc","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:51:03.448Z","parentId":"b1b3be0c-a377-4b2e-834d-d031a1103546"}
